addition.name: Hope For Ethan
addition.intro_content:
Ethan, a 2-year-old autistic boy, loves to laugh, jump, run, play with water, and chase his big sister around the house. But Ethan has no voice. While he communicates by gestures and vocalizations, even a few ASL signs, Ethan is often frustrated by his inability to make himself understood which results in temper tantrums. Ethan has no instincts to tell him to stay near his parents or when something is unsafe; he struggles to sleep more than 60 to 90 minutes at a time during the night and cannot put himself back to sleep or "self soothe." The entire family is exhausted and we are now all experiencing stress-induced illness.

A service dog would be of tremendous help in easing these problems. Through the grace of a service dog: Ethan's chances at verbal communication improve by 70 percent; by tethering, walks or trips to the store will no longer be as challenging and safer; should he become lost, the dog will be able to find him; and with a companion to sleep beside, the whole family will gain a better night’s rest.

As a result, the family has decided to become Ambassadors for Service Dogs by Warren Retrievers (SDWR) - a 501c3 organization. By running a fundraising campaign, Ethan will be placed in cue to receive a dog after they raise $25,000 (Sticker shocked? These dogs cost ~$49,000!). Please consider supporting Ethan and his family by buying a shirt to support their campaign.

For more information about SDWR, visit www.sdwr.org or Ethan's campaign page at http://sdwr.donordrive.com/campaign/ethan.

#adogforethan
addition.intro_header: Buy a t-shirt to help Ethan raise money for SDWR to receive an Autism Service Dog!
addition.pickup_instructions: Shirts will be ready for pickup on August 13 between 10:00am and 1:00pm!

addition.name: Support Childhood Cancer Warriors with Faith Hope & Love
addition.intro_content: Do you know a child who has fought or is currently fighting cancer? We would be honored to INCLUDE THEIR NAME on this t-shirt. Please submit their name exactly as you'd like it to appear in the comments section by August 10, 2016. Shirts will be ready in time for CHILDHOOD CANCER AWARENESS MONTH this September, but we hope you'll wear them all year long!
addition.message_content:
While just about everyone knows what a pink ribbon represents, the average person has no idea that GOLD is the national color for childhood cancer. Let’s work together to raise awareness!

CHILDHOOD CANCER STATISTICS:

- Each year, approximately 300,000 children are diagnosed with cancer.

- More than 40,000 children are in cancer treatment each year in the U.S.

- 1 out of 5 children with cancer will not survive.

- Cancer kills more kids than all other childhood diseases COMBINED.

- 2 out of 3 survivors will suffer devastating long-term effects such as secondary cancers, muscular difficulties, heart disease, learning disabilities, loss of hearing & sight, infertility & more.

- LESS THAN 4% of our nation's total funding of cancer research is dedicated to childhood cancer.

Our children are WORTH MORE THAN 4! Let's wear their names and spread the wordaboutthe realities of childhood cancer with faith, hope & love.
addition.intro_header: Encourage children who are fighting cancer and help raise awareness that they are WORTH MORE THAN 4% of our nation's total funding for cancer research!
addition.pickup_instructions: Shirts will be ready to pick up at Dr. Patel's office in San Antonio, TX on or before September 1, 2016

addition.name: Friends of Shockoe Hill Cemetery
addition.intro_content: The Friends of Shockoe Hill Cemetery was organized in 2006 to promote and maintain the burying ground that served both Richmond’s elite and commonfolk for much of the 19th and 20th centuries. We've been good stewards of the cemetery for ten years now, and need your support to continue our important work.
addition.message_content: The Friends of Shockoe Hill Cemetery was organized in 2006 to promote and maintain the burying ground that served both Richmond’s elite and commonfolk for much of the 19th and 20th centuries. The Friends group began active stewardship with the support of the Enrichmond Foundation and the City of Richmond, and since then has worked to restore damaged grave markers, provide new markers for Civil War veterans, and help maintain and improve the Cemetery grounds. Public outreach is critical to the Friends’ mission. The group organizes regular spring, summer and fall tours, and hosts an annual St. Patrick’s Day event to honor Irish and other immigrants. Members of the Friends are happy to arrange special tours for interested persons and organizations, or to speak at organization meetings. In 2007 the Friends group helped place a state historic marker at the Cemetery. In fact, the group has worked with many organizations, including the Daughters of the American Revolution, the Order of the Southern Cross, and Virginia Civil War Trails, to help fulfill its mission. Besides being the burial place of Chief Justice John Marshall, Shockoe Hill Cemetery is closely tied to the life of Edgar Allan Poe. You will find there the graves of Elmira Shelton, John and Frances Allan, Jane Stanard, and many others who knew and loved him. They are among the many important Virginians who rest here. We invite you to join with us in supporting and caring for this gem of the City!
addition.intro_header: Show your support for the Friends of Shockoe Hill Cemetery!
